                                                                                                            SBI rights this month
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                          Gearing up                                  
	New Delhi, Feb. 8: The rights issue of the State Bank of India (SBI) is likely to open in the third week of February.        
	According to finance ministry officials, the possible date is between February 16 and 18. The rights offer will remain open for one month.        
	Last month, the countrys largest bank had said it would raise Rs 16,700 crore through a rights issue that would double its capital base to help support 25 per cent growth in deposits and advances. It would also allow the SBI to comply with Basel II norms, which relates to capital that must be put aside by banks to meet risks. To keep its holding in the SBI at 59.73 per cent, the government will infuse Rs 10,000 crore.         
	The board of the SBI had agreed that under the rights offer, one share would be issued for every five shares held. The bank had also decided to issue shares to its 2 lakh employees under an employees stock purchase scheme.         
	Each rights share is priced at Rs 1,590  a face value of Rs 10 and a premium of Rs 1,580. Today, the State Bank scrip gained 1.68 per cent to close at Rs 2,191.45.        
	The officials said the bank would go in for a follow-on public offer, if it required capital in the future.         
	According to the officials, The issue has been delayed as approvals from the Reserve Bank of India and the law ministry are still to come. The approvals could come today or tomorrow.         
	The cabinet is expected to take up next week the terms and conditions of the merger of the State Bank of Saurashtra with its parent, the SBI.                                                                                                                                       
